Avoid rebuilding the PEG parser matcher per default macro

Parser::GetCache() builds a fresh ParserCache (the full PEG grammar matcher +
transformer factory, ~0.6-0.9 ms each) whenever a Parser is constructed
without options.parser_cache. The default-macro paths do exactly that:
DefaultFunctionGenerator::CreateInternalMacroInfo and
DefaultTableFunctionGenerator::CreateTableMacroInfo construct bare Parsers,
so every database instantiation rebuilds the grammar once per JSON extension
macro, and every lazily created default (table) macro rebuilds it again.

Plumb ParserOptions through the default generators (from
ClientContext::GetParserOptions in the on-demand catalog path, and from the
DatabaseInstance's ParserCache in the JSON extension's load path), keeping
the existing signatures as compatibility overloads.

Measured on an M-series mac: in-memory database open drops from ~10.7 ms to
~5.8 ms (the remaining cost is dominated by static extension function
registration and the per-instance grammar build on first parse).


